{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517936"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:58:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:58:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12852"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12852"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.03,0.46,0.2,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60118"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5295"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12852"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45538"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18870"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60118"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents with a two month history of worsening headaches. Seven months ago he was diagnosed with migraine headaches, due to headaches that occurred five times per month. He was started on propranolol daily as prophylaxis, as well as sumatriptan for abortive therapy, used about 4-5 times per month. Despite this, his headaches worsened to ten times per month and so he started taking sumatriptan daily. His current headaches (for the last two months) have been occuring daily, are bilateral, pressing in nature, and typically last for several hours. He states that the pain intensity fluctuates throughout the day and is not relieved by any analgesic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension, both diagnosed five years ago, for which he is taking metformin and amlodipine respectively. He also has a history of bilateral knee osteoarthritis. He occasionally takes naproxen when needed, usually twice in a week, prior to going on his regular hikes. His neurological examination is unremarkable. Various investigations including an MRI brain are performed, without any abnormalities being found.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely responsible for his presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amlodipine","Metformin","Sumatriptan","Naproxen","Propranolol"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario has a medication overuse headache, which typically develops in patients with headache disorders (like migraine) who overuse analgesic medications like NSAIDs, triptans and opiates. While they use these medications to alleviate symptoms of their primary headache disorder, unfortunately the medication overuse becomes a cause of their headaches. The diagnostic criteria for the diagnosis of medication overuse headache is as follows\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeadache occurring on \u226515 days/month in a patient with a pre-existing headache disorder\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular overuse for \u0026gt;3 months of one or more drugs that can be taken for acute and/or symptomatic treatment of headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENot better accounted for by another ICHD-3 diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESumatriptan \u003C/strong\u003Eis the drug in this scenario responsible for this patient\u0027s symptoms since he has been continuously taking this for more than 10 days per month which is a diagnostic criterion for medication overuse headache due to triptans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaproxen \u003C/strong\u003E(an NSAID) has the potential to cause medication overuse headaches, but it needs to be taken for more than 15 days per month to cause medication overuse headaches and since the patient uses it only twice a week, it is an unlikely cause of this patient\u0027s signs and symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol \u003C/strong\u003E(a beta blocker)\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis used as a preventive drug for migraine and is not associated with medication overuse headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine (\u003C/strong\u003Ea calcium channel blocker) is not usually associated with medication overuse headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E (a biguanide) is not usually associated with medication overuse headache.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The use of triptans for more than 10 days per month is associated with the development of medication overuse headaches."],"references":["Fischer MA, Jan A. Medication-overuse Headache. [Updated 2022 Jul 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538150/","Headache Classification Committee of the International Headache Society (IHS) The International Classification of Headache Disorders, 3rd edition. Cephalalgia. 2018 Jan;38(1):1-211."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45538"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12852"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45538","links":{"self